{{broader|Developed country}}
[[File:World Map - Developed Markets.jpg|thumb|Developed markets, according to the three data providers FTSE, MSCI and S&P.
{{legend|#013397|recognized as a developed market by all of these}}
{{legend|#0c7ff1|recognized as a developed markets by a majority of these}}
{{legend|#0cd5f1|recognized as a developed markets by a minority of these}}]]

In [[investing]], a '''developed market''' is a country that is most developed in terms of its economy and capital markets. The country must be high income, but this also includes openness to foreign ownership, ease of capital movement, and efficiency of market institutions. This term is contrasted with [[developing market]] ([[Emerging markets]] and [[frontier markets]] are types of developing markets).

==FTSE Group list==
[[FTSE Group]], a provider of economic and financial data, assigns the market status of countries as Developed, Advanced Emerging, Secondary Emerging or Frontier on the basis of their economic size, wealth, quality of markets, depth of markets, breadth of markets.
From 24 September 2018, FTSE Group classifies 25 countries as developed markets:<ref>[http://www.ftse.com/Analytics/FactSheets/Home/DownloadSingleIssue?issueName=AWD FTSE Developed Index, p. 3.]</ref><ref>[http://www.mondovisione.com/media-and-resources/news/ftse-russell-reclassifies-poland-to-developed-market-status/ FTSE Russell Reclassifies Poland To Developed Market Status]</ref>
