[[File:Jerusalem, Kikar Safra 01.jpg|thumb|flags of Hapoel on Safra square in Jerusalem]] '''Hapoel''' ({{lang-he-n|הפועל}}, lit. ''the worker'') is an [[Israel]]i sport association established in 1926 by the [[Histadrut]] Labor Federation.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=R0pSCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&dq=hapoel+1926&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi-mobJ3bvQAhVKKiYKHYmkCkoQ6AEIIzAB#v=onepage&q=hapoel%201926&f=false ''Playing as if the World Mattered: An Illustrated History of Activism in Sports'' - Gabriel Kuhn<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=oeF4KF9diy4C&pg=PA145&dq=hapoel+1926&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi-mobJ3bvQAhVKKiYKHYmkCkoQ6AEILjAD#v=onepage&q=hapoel%201926&f=false ''Europe, Sport, World: Shaping Global Societies'' - J. A. Mangan<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> ==History== During the [[British Mandate for Palestine (legal instrument)|British Mandate of Palestine]] period Hapoel had a bitter rivalry with [[Maccabi World Union|Maccabi]] and organized its own competitions, with the exception of [[Israel Football Association|football]], the only sport in which all the organizations played each other. At the time, Hapoel took no part in the ''Eretz Israel Olympic Committee'', which was controlled by Maccabi, and instead sought for international ties with similar workers sports organizations of socialist parties. Therefore, Hapoel became a member of [[Socialist Workers' Sport International|SASI]] in 1927 and later was a member of [[CSIT]].
After the State of Israel was established, the rival sport organizations reached a 1951 agreement that allowed joint sports associations and competitions open for all Israeli residents. [[File:Hapoel crest.svg|thumb|Hapoel crest uses a variation of the communist symbol, the [[Hammer and sickle]] and a [[Boxing|Boxer]]]]
